article.description: Shyra Ely had 17 points and 11 rebounds to lead third-ranked Tennessee to an 85-65 victory over No. 10 Louisiana Tech on Sunday.
article.headline: Lady Vols led by as many as 17 in second half
article.linkText: No. 3 Tennessee holds No. 10 LaTech at bay
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Former Lady Vol Tamika Catchings slipped
in some practice time at Tennessee while in town to celebrate the
retirement of her number.

Looking inspired by their former teammate, the third-ranked Lady
Vols beat No. 10 Louisiana Tech 85-65 on Sunday.

"She made me want to play so much better, work so much harder.
I wanted to guard her. I wanted her to guard me (in practice),"
said Shyra Ely, who led Tennessee with 17 points and 11 rebounds.

The Lady Vols (3-0) took control midway through the first half
and stretched their lead to 17 points with 8:38 remaining.

The Lady Techsters (3-1), who have lost four straight to
Tennessee, cut the lead to six on Amisha Carter's basket with 17:47
remaining, but that was as close as they would get the rest of the
way. They shot just 23 percent in the second half.

Loree Moore had two baskets and Shanna Zolman hit a 3 to start a
14-5 run for Tennessee, which reserve Brittany Jackson capped with
a driving layup and 3-pointer that increased the lead to 61-46 with
12:29 left.

Zolman finished with 15 points, while Jackson had 14 and Moore
10.

Catchings' No. 24 was retired at halftime. She received a
standing ovation when she was introduced at midcourt with her
parents and sister.

Catchings, a two-time WNBA All-Star with the Indiana Fever best
known for her all-out hustle at Tennessee, practiced with the team
this week.

"I thought she served as an inspiration for our players in
practice. She was blocking shots into the stands," Tennessee coach
Pat Summitt said. "I've shared a number of times with them what
kind of player I think Tamika Catchings is."

Carter led Louisiana Tech in scoring with 17 points. Trina
Frierson had 11 points and 10 rebounds and reserve Lakiste Barkus
and Erica Smith-Taylor each added 10.

The 36th meeting between the teams was marked with bursts of
transition as they combined for 27 steals and 41 turnovers.

Louisiana Tech guard Aarica Ray-Boyd was injured with 1:05
remaining and taken away in an ambulance. She fell hard after being
hit in the forehead with an elbow while trying to block a
3-pointer, and lost consciousness for about 45 seconds.

Ray-Boyd was taken to University of Tennessee Medical Center and
was diagnosed with a mild concussion, but was not admitted, team
spokesman Malcolm Butler said.

She left Knoxville with the team and with "a big headache,"
Butler said.

Ray-Boyd leaped high to try to block a shot by Tennessee's
Dominique Redding. She lay motionless for several minutes while
trainers from both teams and the coaches stood over her, then
finally moved her arms and blinked.

Louisiana Tech coach Kurt Budke said Ray-Boyd was hit in the
forehead by Redding's elbow.

Trailing by six with 8:17 left in the first half, Tennessee
outscored Louisiana Tech 25-12 the rest of the way to lead 45-38 at
halftime.

The Lady Vols were ahead 10-2 in the opening minutes, but
Louisiana Tech kept chipping away at the lead and put together a
10-0 run to go ahead.

Barkus had a 3 and made another off a rebound that put the Lady
Techsters ahead 26-20.

Tennessee switched to a zone defense, and Moore broke the
scoreless streak with a free throw to start the Lady Vols' run.

"They expose any weakness you might have as a team," Budke
said.

Tennessee and Louisiana Tech are the only women's programs with
more than 700 wins.
